<subSubSection id="C34DFA9CFFC0FF8AD471F9C3D805F98B" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="517" pageId="1" pageNumber="516" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE8A917FFC0FF8AD471F9C3D805F98B" blockId="1.[809,1453,1652,1959]" lastBlockId="2.[136,779,1239,1610]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="517" pageId="1" pageNumber="516">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC0FF89D471F9C3DAC5F946" bold="true" box="[809,921,1652,1671]" pageId="1" pageNumber="516">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C57D294FFC0FF89D4C6F9C3DAB5F946" authorityName="Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann" authorityYear="1888" box="[926,1001,1652,1671]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Hassar" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="516" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC0FF89D4C6F9C3DAB5F946" box="[926,1001,1652,1671]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="516">Hassar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed by a single exclusive character: basioccipital with a ventral ring-like arch surrounding aorta (
<figureCitation id="136CB592FFC0FF89D469F903DA37F906" box="[817,875,1716,1735]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[136,175,1007,1026]" captionTargetBox="[136,779,197,970]" captionTargetId="figure-681@2.[136,779,197,970]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Anteriormost vertebrae and associated structures, in ventral view, of Hassar orestis, MZUSP 105827, 144.7 mm SL. BAS, basioccipital; CV, complex vertebra; Mr, Müllerian ramus; pEPO, epioccipital process; pTR, transcapular process; SCL, posttemporo-supracleithrum; TRI, tripus. Arrow indicates the ring-shaped ventral arch of the basioccipital. Scale bar = 5 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5422998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5422998/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="516">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); and by the combination of the following non-exclusive characters: 1) dark blotch in the middle to distal region of anterior branched rays of dorsal fin; 2) anteriormost postinfranuchal scutes reduced in size; 3) pores beneath the posterior cleithral process numerous; 4) maxillary barbels with 7 to 16 secondary barbels, and fleshy papillae restricted to anteriormost secondary barbels; 5) elongated mesethmoid, with lanceolate anterior tip and straight to slightly convex dorsal profile; 6) posterior cranial fontanel relatively large, extending posteriorly into the parietosupraoccipital; 7) first infraorbital long and slender, with dilated anterior extremity, articulating with the lateral border of mesethmoid; 8) ossified and extremely well-developed epioccipital process, sutured to the posterior nuchal plate; 9) less than 10 premaxillary teeth; 10) less than 20 dentary teeth; 11) well-developed nuchal foramina; 12) reduced anterior nuchal plate, enclosed by the posterior margin of the parietosupraoccipital and anterior margin of the middle nuchal plate; 13) 30 to 34 midlateral scutes on each side of body. See Discussion for additional notes on the aforementioned diagnostic features.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption id="DF28F99FFFC3FF8AD7D0FC58DA56FB63" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5422998" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5422998" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5422998/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" startId="2.[136,175,1007,1026]" targetBox="[136,779,197,970]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8BE8A917FFC3FF8AD7D0FC58DA56FB63" blockId="2.[136,779,1007,1186]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD7D0FC58D98CFBC3" bold="true" box="[136,208,1007,1026]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Fig. 1.</emphasis>
Anteriormost vertebrae and associated structures, in ventral view, of 
<taxonomicName id="4C57D294FFC3FF8AD671FBB8DB41FBE3" authority=", MZUSP" authorityName="MZUSP" box="[297,541,1039,1058]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Hassar" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="orestis">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD671FBB8D8E0FBE3" box="[297,444,1039,1058]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Hassar orestis</emphasis>
, MZUSP
</taxonomicName>
105827, 144.7 mm SL. BAS, basioccipital; CV, complex vertebra; Mr, Müllerian ramus; pEPO, epioccipital process; pTR, transcapular process; SCL, posttemporo-supracleithrum; TRI, 
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD6ADFBD8DB6FFB43" box="[501,563,1135,1154]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">tripus</emphasis>
. Arrow indicates the ring-shaped ventral arch of the basioccipital. Scale bar = 5 mm
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection id="C34DFA9CFFC3FF8AD7D0F9C0DB97F92B" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BE8A917FFC3FF8AD7D0F9C0DB97F92B" blockId="2.[136,778,1655,1770]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD7D0F9C0D85EF94B" bold="true" box="[136,258,1655,1674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Etymology.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFC6D4E6FFC3FF8AD65EF9C0DB0EF94B" author="Eigenmann, C" box="[262,594,1655,1674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" pagination="119 - 172" refId="ref21893" refString="Eigenmann, C. H. &amp; R. S. Eigenmann. 1888. Preliminary notes on South American Nematognathi. I. Proceedings California Academy of Sciences, 1: 119 - 172." type="journal article" year="1888">Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann (1888)</bibRefCitation>
did not specify the origin of 
<taxonomicName id="4C57D294FFC3FF8AD7B0F920D868F96B" authorityName="Eigenmann &amp; Eigenmann" authorityYear="1888" box="[232,308,1687,1706]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Doradidae" genus="Hassar" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD7B0F920D868F96B" box="[232,308,1687,1706]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Hassar</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but it possibly refers to the name commonly applied to certain catfishes in 
<collectingCountry id="F340E987FFC3FF8AD69AF900DB4BF90B" box="[450,535,1719,1738]" name="Guyana" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Guyana</collectingCountry>
, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C57D294FFC3FF8AD52BF900D981F92B" baseAuthorityName="Hancock" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Actinopterygii" family="Callichthyidae" genus="Hoplosternum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="littorale">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD52BF900D981F92B" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Hoplosternum littorale</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="4C57D294FFC3FF8AD7A6F960DB9BF92B" authority="(Eigenmann, 1912)" baseAuthorityName="Eigenmann" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[254,711,1751,1770]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Hypostomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="watawata">
<emphasis id="B9237505FFC3FF8AD7A6F960D8ACF92B" box="[254,496,1751,1770]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="517">Hypostomus watawata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFC6D4E6FFC3FF8AD6A5F960DBE3F92B" author="Eigenmann, C" box="[509,703,1751,1770]" pageId="2" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 578" refId="ref21729" refString="Eigenmann, C. H. 1912. The freshwater fishes of British Guiana, including a study of the ecological grouping of species, and the relation of the fauna of the plateau to that to the lowlands. Memoirs Carnegie Museum, 5: i-xxii + 1 - 578." type="journal article" year="1912">Eigenmann, 1912</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
